  "prompt": "Am I pregnant? We used a condom it did not break but I think I was fertile that time. I took nordette though",
  "response": "It\u2019s understandable to feel concerned, but let\u2019s break this down:\n\n1. **Condom Use**: If the condom was used correctly and did not break, slip off, or leak, it is highly effective at preventing pregnancy. The typical use failure rate is around 13%, but with perfect use, it\u2019s about 2%.\n\n2. **Fertility**: Even if you were fertile at the time, the condom would have greatly reduced the risk of pregnancy.\n\n3. **Nordette**: Nordette is an emergency contraceptive pill (morning-after pill). If taken within 72 hours after unprotected sex, it significantly reduces the risk of pregnancy by preventing ovulation, fertilization, or implantation, depending on where you are in your cycle. However, it\u2019s not 100% effective, and its effectiveness decreases the longer you wait to take it.\n\n**What to Do Next**  \nTo ease your concerns:  \n- Take a **pregnancy test** if your period is late. Pregnancy tests are most accurate when taken about 1\u20132 weeks after a missed period.  \n- Watch for early pregnancy symptoms (e.g., missed period, nausea, breast tenderness), but remember these can also be caused by other factors like stress or hormonal changes.  \n- If you\u2019re still worried, consult a healthcare provider for reassurance or further guidance. \n\nThe combination of condom use and emergency contraception significantly lowers your chances of pregnancy, but a test can provide clarity.",
